{
  "doc_id": "24023",
  "text": "Here we demonstrated that inactivating one hemisphere in adult mouse V1 significantly reduced ipsilateral eye evoked activity in the entire binocular part of V1 of the opposite hemisphere. These data emphasize that also in adult mouse V1, cortico-cortical interactions play a major role for determining ocular dominance, and thus significantly extend previous knowledge about callosal influences on binocularity in juvenile rats [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Our data are also in line with recent extracellular single unit recordings in PD90 mice showing that the ipsilateral eye's response was reduced by removing the callosal input [CITATION_4] . Here we demonstrate that the enhancing effect of cortico-cortical interactions on visually driven ipsilateral eye activity can also be observed in the population response, i.e. is a rather general influence, and also extends over the entire binocular part of V1.",
